The photocatalytic stability of the Pt-NLCDs@CdS composite was further evaluated in a 60 h continuous photocatalytic water splitting experiment. As shown in Fig. 7
                        f, at the initial stage of the experiment, the PHE rate of Pt-NLCDs@CdS increases rapidly with the extension of the reaction time, and reaches the extreme value (50.32 mmol·h−1·g−1) at 7th hour. Then the PHE rate begins to decrease gradually (but remained at a high level) and decreases to 37.57 mmol·h−1·g−1 at the 30th hour. It is found that this decline does not mean the failure of the photocatalyst, but caused by the consumption of sacrificial agent. After replenishing 5 mL LA, the PHE rate rebounded to 41.24 mmol·h−1·g−1 at the 49th hour. Noting that the PHE rate can remain above 38 mmol·h−1·g−1 even after 60 h continuous experiment, revealing the excellent photostability of Pt-NLCDs@CdS, which can also be proved by the five cycling tests (
                           Figure S10

                        ), the XRD (
                           Figure S11
                        ) and FTIR (
                           Figure S12
                        ) results of the photocatalysts before and after the cycling test. In addition, by comparing the XPS spectra (
                           Figure S13
                        ) of fresh and used photocatalysts, it is found that the peak locations of C 1 s, S 2p and Cd 3d core lines remained unchanged, while their peak intensities changed slightly, confirming the excellent stability of the ternary Pt-NLCDs@CdS composite.
